.PP
To send packets (outbound) on the returned \fISocket\fR, use \fIsend/2\fR. Packets sent from the peer (inbound) are delivered as messages to the socket owner; the process that created the socket. Unless \fI{active, false}\fR is specified in the option list when creating the listening socket.

.PP
See \fIconnect/4\fR about \fIactive mode\fR socket messages and \fIpassive mode\fR.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThe \fIaccept\fR call \fIdoesn't have to be\fR issued from the socket owner process. Using version 5.5.3 and higher of the emulator, multiple simultaneous accept calls can be issued from different processes, which allows for a pool of acceptor processes handling incoming connections.



.RE
.B
\fBclose(Socket) -> ok when Socket :: socket().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Close a TCP socket.

.PP
Note that in most implementations of TCP, doing a \fIclose\fR does not guarantee that the data sent is delivered to the recipient.  It is guaranteed that the recepient will see all sent data before getting the close, but the sender gets no indication of that.

.PP
If the sender needs to know that the recepient has received all data there are two common ways to achieve this:

.nr li 0 1
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\n+[li].\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP "\n+[li]." 4
.\}.PP
Use \fIgen_tcp:shutdown(Sock, write)\fR to signal that no more data is to be sent and wait for the other side to acknowledge seeing its read side being closed, by closing its write side, which shows as a socket close on this side.

.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\n+[li].\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP "\n+[li]." 4
.\}.PP
Implement an acknowledgement in the protocol on top of TCP that both connection ends adhere to, indicating that all data has been seen.  The socket option \fI{packet, N}\fR may be useful.

.RE


.RE
