.PP
Create a socket connected to the specified address.

.PP
Creates a socket and connects it to a server on TCP port \fIPort\fR on the host with IP address \fIAddress\fR, that may also be a hostname.

.PP
\fB\fIOpts\fR\fR\fB (connect options)\fR

{ip, Address}
.RS 2
If the local host has many IP addresses, this option specifies which one to use.


.RE

{ifaddr, Address}
.RS 2
Same as 
\fI{ip, Address}\fR.
.PP
However, if \fIAddress\fR instead is a \fIsocket:sockaddr_in/0\fR or \fIsocket:sockaddr_in6/0\fR this takes precedence over any value previously set with the \fIip\fR and \fIport\fR options. If these options (\fIip\fR or/and \fIport\fR) however comes \fIafter\fR this option, they may be used to \fIupdate\fR the corresponding fields of this option (for \fIip\fR, the \fIaddr\fR field, and for \fIport\fR, the \fIport\fR field).


.RE

{fd, integer() >= 0}
.RS 2
If a socket has somehow been connected without using 
\fIgen_tcp\fR, use this option to pass the file descriptor for it. If \fI{ip, Address}\fR and/or \fI{port, port_number()}\fR is combined with this option, the \fIfd\fR is bound to the specified interface and port before connecting. If these options are not specified, it is assumed that the \fIfd\fR is already bound appropriately.

.RE

inet
.RS 2
Sets up the socket for IPv4.


.RE

inet6
.RS 2
Sets up the socket for IPv6.


.RE

local
.RS 2
Sets up a Unix Domain Socket. See 
\fIinet:local_address/0\fR

.RE

{port, Port}
.RS 2
Specifies which local port number to use.


.RE

{tcp_module, module()}
.RS 2
Overrides which callback module is used. Defaults to 
\fIinet_tcp\fR for IPv4 and \fIinet6_tcp\fR for IPv6.

.RE

{protocol, tcp|mptcp}
.RS 2
With 
\fImptcp\fR creates the socket with protocol IPPROTO_MPTCP, if that is defined on the system. Other than that the socket is regarded as a \fItcp\fR socket. If IPPROTO_MPTCP is not defined, \fI{error, eprotonosupport}\fR is returned. \fItcp\fR is the default value.

.RE

option/0
.RS 2
See 
\fIinet:setopts/2\fR.

.RE

.PP
\fBSocket Data\fR

.PP
Packets can be sent to the peer (outbound) with \fIsend(Socket, Packet)\fR.  Packets sent from the peer (inbound) are delivered as messages to the socket owner; the process that created the socket, unless \fI{active, false}\fR is specified in the \fIOptions\fR list.

.PP
\fBActive mode socket messages\fR

{tcp, Socket, Data}
.RS 2
Inbound data from the socket.


.RE

{tcp_passive, Socket}
.RS 2
The socket was in 
\fI{active, N}\fR mode (see \fIinet:setopts/2\fR for details) and its message counter reached \fI0\fR, indicating that the socket has transitioned to passive (\fI{active, false}\fR) mode.

.RE

{tcp_closed, Socket}
.RS 2
The socket was closed.


.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fI{tcp_error, Socket, Reason}\fR\fR A socket error occurred.

.RE

.PP
\fBPassive mode\fR

.PP
If \fI{active, false}\fR is specified in the option list for the socket, packets and errors are retrieved by calling \fIrecv/2,3\fR (\fIsend/2\fR may also return errors).

.PP
\fBTimeout\fR

.PP
The optional \fITimeout\fR parameter specifies a connect time-out in milliseconds. Defaults to \fIinfinity\fR.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRKeep in mind that if the underlying OS \fIconnect()\fR call returns a timeout, \fIgen_tcp:connect\fR will also return a timeout (i.e. \fI{error, etimedout}\fR), even if a larger \fITimeout\fR was specified (for example \fIinfinity\fR).


.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThe default values for options specified to \fIconnect\fR can be affected by the Kernel configuration parameter \fIinet_default_connect_options\fR. For details, see \fIinet\fR.



.RE
.B
\fBcontrolling_process(Socket, Pid) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                             when\fR
\fB                                 Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                                 Pid :: pid(),\fR
\fB                                 Reason ::\fR
\fB                                     closed | not_owner | badarg |\fR
\fB                                     inet:posix().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Change the controlling process (owner) of a socket.

.PP
Assigns a new controlling process \fIPid\fR to \fISocket\fR. The controlling process is the process that the socket sends messages to.  If this function is called from any other process than the current controlling process, \fI{error, not_owner}\fR is returned.

.PP
If the process identified by \fIPid\fR is not an existing local \fIpid/0\fR, \fI{error, badarg}\fR is returned. \fI{error, badarg}\fR may also be returned in some cases when \fISocket\fR is closed during the execution of this function.

.PP
If the socket is in \fIactive mode\fR, this function will transfer any messages from the socket in the mailbox of the caller to the new controlling process.

.PP
If any other process is interacting with the socket during the transfer, it may not work correctly and messages may remain in the caller's mailbox. For instance, changing the sockets active mode during the transfer could cause this.


.RE
.B
\fBlisten(Port, Options) -> {ok, ListenSocket} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    Port :: inet:port_number(),\fR
\fB                    Options :: [inet:inet_backend() | listen_option()],\fR
\fB                    ListenSocket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    Reason :: system_limit | inet:posix().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Create a listen socket.

.PP
Creates a socket and sets it to listen on port \fIPort\fR on the local host.

.PP
If \fIPort == 0\fR, the underlying OS assigns an available (ephemeral) port number, use \fIinet:port/1\fR to retrieve it.

.PP
The following options are available:

list
.RS 2
Received 
\fIPacket\fRs are delivered as lists of bytes, \fI\fR[\fIbyte/0\fR\fI]\fR.

.RE

binary
.RS 2
Received 
\fIPacket\fRs are delivered as \fIbinary/0\fRs.

.RE

{backlog, B}
.RS 2

\fIB ::\fR \fInon_neg_integer/0\fR. The backlog value defines the maximum length that the queue of pending connections can grow to. Defaults to \fI5\fR.

.RE

inet6
.RS 2
Sets up the socket for IPv6.


.RE

inet
.RS 2
Sets up the socket for IPv4.


.RE

{fd, Fd}
.RS 2
If a socket has somehow been created without using 
\fIgen_tcp\fR, use this option to pass the file descriptor for it.

.RE

{ip, Address}
.RS 2
If the host has many IP addresses, this option specifies which one to listen on.


.RE

{port, Port}
.RS 2
Specifies which local port number to use.


.RE

{ifaddr, Address}
.RS 2
Same as 
\fI{ip, Address}\fR.
.PP
However, if this instead is an \fIsocket:sockaddr_in/0\fR or \fIsocket:sockaddr_in6/0\fR this takes precedence over any value previously set with the \fIip\fR and \fIport\fR options. If these options (\fIip\fR or/and \fIport\fR) however comes \fIafter\fR this option, they may be used to \fIupdate\fR their corresponding fields of this option (for \fIip\fR, the \fIaddr\fR field, and for \fIport\fR, the \fIport\fR field).


.RE

{tcp_module, module()}
.RS 2
Overrides which callback module is used. Defaults to 
\fIinet_tcp\fR for IPv4 and \fIinet6_tcp\fR for IPv6.

.RE

{protocol, tcp|mptcp}
.RS 2
With 
\fImptcp\fR creates the socket with protocol IPPROTO_MPTCP, if that is defined on the system. Other than that the socket is regarded as a \fItcp\fR socket. If IPPROTO_MPTCP is not defined, \fI{error, eprotonosupport}\fR is returned. \fItcp\fR is the default value.

.RE

option/0
.RS 2
See 
\fIinet:setopts/2\fR.

.RE

.PP
The returned socket \fIListenSocket\fR should be used when calling \fIaccept/1,2\fR to accept an incoming connection request.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThe default values for options specified to \fIlisten\fR can be affected by the Kernel configuration parameter \fIinet_default_listen_options\fR. For details, see \fIinet\fR.



.RE
.B
\fBrecv(Socket, Length, Timeout) -> {ok, Packet} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                  Length :: non_neg_integer(),\fR
\fB                  Timeout :: timeout(),\fR
\fB                  Packet :: string() | binary() | HttpPacket,\fR
\fB                  Reason :: closed | timeout | inet:posix(),\fR
\fB                  HttpPacket :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Receive a packet, from a socket in \fIpassive mode\fR.

.PP
A closed socket is indicated by the return value \fI{error, closed}\fR. If the socket is not in passive mode, the return value is \fI{error, einval}\fR.

.PP
Argument \fILength\fR is only meaningful when the socket is in \fIraw\fR mode and denotes the number of bytes to read.  If \fILength\fR is \fI0\fR, all available bytes are returned. If \fILength > 0\fR, exactly \fILength\fR bytes are returned, or an error; except if the socket is closed from the other side, then the last read before the one returning \fI{error, closed}\fR may return less than \fILength\fR bytes of data.

.PP
The optional \fITimeout\fR parameter specifies a time-out in milliseconds. Defaults to \fIinfinity\fR.

.PP
Any process can receive data from a passive socket, even if that process is not the controlling process of the socket. However, only one process can call this function on a socket at any given time. Using simultaneous calls to \fIrecv\fR is not recommended as the behavior depends on the socket implementation, and could return errors such as \fI{error, ealready}\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBsend(Socket, Packet) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                  Packet :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                  Reason :: closed | {timeout, RestData} | inet:posix(),\fR
\fB                  RestData :: binary() | erlang:iovec().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Send a packet on a socket.

.PP
There is no \fIsend/2\fR call with a time-out option; use socket option \fIsend_timeout\fR if time-outs are desired.  See section Examples.

.PP
The return value \fI{error, {timeout, RestData}}\fR can only be returned when \fIinet_backend = socket\fR.

.RS 4
.PP
\fBNote \fR

.PP
\fBNon-blocking send.\fR

.PP
If the user tries to send more data than there is room for in the OS send buffers, the 'rest data' is stored in (inet driver) internal buffers and later sent in the background. The function immediately returns ok (\fInot\fR informing the caller that some date isn'nt sent yet). Any issue while sending the 'rest data' may be returned later. When using \fIinet_backend = socket\fR, the behaviour is different. There is \fIno\fR buffering, instead the caller will "hang" until all of the data has been sent or the send timeout (as specified by the \fIsend_timeout\fR option) expires (the function can "hang" even when using the \fIinet\fR backend if the internal buffers are full). If this happens when using \fIpacket =/= raw\fR, a partial packet has been written. A new packet therefore \fImustn't\fR be written at this point, as there is no way for the peer to distinguish this from data in the current packet. Instead, set the \fIpacket\fR option to \fIraw\fR, send the rest data (as raw data) and then set \fIpacket\fR back to the correct type.

.RE


.RE
.B
\fBshutdown(Socket, How) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                  when\fR
\fB                      Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                      How :: read | write | read_write,\fR
\fB                      Reason :: inet:posix().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Close the socket in one or both directions.

.PP
\fIHow == write\fR means closing the socket for writing, reading from it is still possible.

.PP
If \fIHow == read\fR or there is no outgoing data buffered in the \fISocket\fR port, the shutdown is performed immediately and any error encountered is returned in \fIReason\fR.

.PP
If there is data buffered in the socket port, shutdown isn't performed on the socket until that buffered data has been written to the OS protocol stack.  If any errors are encountered, the socket is closed and \fI{error, closed}\fR is returned by the next \fIrecv/2\fR or \fIsend/2\fR call.

.PP
Option \fI{exit_on_close, false}\fR is useful if the peer performs a shutdown of its write side.  Then the socket stays open for writing after receive has indicated that the socket was closed.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRAsync shutdown write (\fIHow :: write | read_write\fR). If the shutdown attempt is made while the inet driver is sending buffered data in the background, the shutdown is postponed until all buffered data has been sent.  This function immediately returns \fIok\fR, and the caller \fIisn't\fR informed (that the shutdown has been postponed). When using \fIinet_backend = socket\fR, the behaviour is different. A shutdown with \fIHow :: write | read_write\fR will always be performed \fIimmediately\fR.



.RE
